Tim Ferriss
-------------
Why you should define your fears instead of your goals
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5J6jAC6XxAI
Tried to commit suicide. College student in a downward spiral who feels helpless and hopeless.
I became very methodical about testing different ways I could manage my ups and downs. 
I decided I would share my recipe for avoiding self destruction. And self paralysis. 
And the tool I found whcih have proven to be the most reliable safety net for emotional free fall is stoicism. 
Stoicism has spread like wild fire as a mean of mental toughness training. 
Think at stoicism as an operating system for thriving in high stress environments, for making better decisions. 
In the Greco-Roman world, people used stoicism as a comprehensive system for doing many things, 
but for our purposes, chief among them was training yourself to separate what you can control from what you cannot control. 
And then doing exercices to focus exclusively on the former. This decreases emotional reactivity, which can be a super power. 
There are many tools in the toolkit to get you there. I'm gonna focus on one that completely changed my life. 
Seneca: 'We suffer more often in imagination than in reality.' 
Pre-meditation of evils. Visualizing the worse-case scenario in detail that you fear, preventing you from taking actions, so you can take actions, overcome that paralysis. 
My problem was, monkey mind, very loud, super incessant. Just thinking my way through problems doesn't work. 
I needed to catch my thoughts on paper, so I created a written exercise that I called fear setting. 
It consists of three pages. First page: What if.. This is whatever you fear, whatever is causing you anxiety. 3 columns: define, prevent, repair. 
Define all the worst case scenarios that could happen if you take that step. 
Prevent: what could i do to prevent these from happening, or to decrease their likelihood. 
Repai: if the worst case scenario has happened, what can you do to repair the damage, even a little bit. Ask yourself, has anyone else in the history of time, less intelligent or less driven, figured this out? Chances are, the answer is yes. 
The second page: what might be the benefits of an attempt (if you attempted what you're afraid of doing) or partial success (at doing what you're afraid of doing)? Might you build confidence? Might you develop skills? Emotionally, financially, ..?
Page three: the cost of inaction. The might be the most important so don't skip it. Humans are very good at considering what might go wrong, if we try something new. 
What we don't often consider is the atrocious cost of the status quo, of not changing anything. 
So, you should ask yourself, if i avoid this action or decision, what might my life look like in say 6 months, 1 year, 3 years. And really get detailed, again, emotionally (relationships, personal), financially, physically, whatever. 
And when I did this it painted a terrifying picture. I realized inaction was no longer an option for me. 
Those are three pages, that's it, that's fear setting. 
If i did this, I was risking a 1 to 3 of temporary and reversible pain, for an 8 to 10 of positive, life-changing impact that could be semi-permanent. 
So I took the trip, ended up extending that trip for a year and a half around the world, and that became the basis for my first book.
Do fear setting at least once a quarter. 
You'll find that some of your fears are very well founded, but you shouldn't conclude that without first putting them under a microscope. 
'Easy choices, hard life. Hard choices, easy life.' Jerzy Gregorek
The hard choices, what we most fear doing, saying, asking, these are very often what we most need to do. 


